Ask HN: How do you find your local community? (Austin, TX)
text:
Hi all,

I'm struggling to find like-minded people. This is both an online and in person conundrum for me.

I moved to the US many moons ago and have been in a creative field that barely crosses over into technical and I don't know where I'd go for meetups or otherwise!

I've tried reaching out/interacting with individuals in my area through the typical social media channels but I'm just another nobody so I feel in person is the best way to make an impression.

I'm currently in Austin and am looking for folks interested in reversing/sdr/general hackery. HN, do you know how best to make introductions or find new folk?

This is as much a hope for a career shift as it is just making new friends. It's quite isolating! Appreciate any advice you all could give!

Ask HN: Solo Developers, what tools do you use to keep track of features/tasks?
text:
I'm working on a few different software projects, mostly for fun, but I think they could benefit others one day once I get them squared away.

I was using Trello to keep track of the different features, and tasks required to get the app to the next level.

I'm finding that Trello is too limited in what I can do to keep track of all the different breakdowns of tasks, and that gets in the way of being productive or keeping good notes on them.

On the other end of the spectrum, JIRA is way too intense. Everything can be configured, and when I used it previously, the UX was hostile and unhelpful for quickly jotting down tasks, ideas, and other needs to go from nothing to a feature.

What software do you use to keep track of these things?

Is there a goldilocks software that is neither too basic, nor to byzantinely configurable, but rather hits that sweet spot for productivity?

title: Consciousness and Quantum Mechanics: What's the Link?
Show HN: Search and download UI code from across the web
text: I made this to simplify UI creation for developers. I use the Chrome console to reference how UI is built, but finding it in the first place is a bit of a pain. It also strikes me how npm has a lot of component and component libraries published there but there isn't a visual way to search and browse them. This is a first attempt by simply scraping UI code and presenting it a visual, searchable way.

Ask HN: Refusing 24x7, What's Your Experience?
text:
Anyone out there refuse to go on 24x7? How'd you do it? What was your experience?

US here. They flipped 24x7 on 3 of us on our team, no warning, 3PM Friday, before week long holiday. I'm furious and I'm trying to figure out best way to proceed.

I didn't say "no" on Friday, even though I'm perfectly comfortable saying it, because it would have screwed my 2 coworkers over (who were equally undeserving of the decision), so trying to figure out strategy for when we get back. Would love to hear about your experiences.

Thank you
